WEBVTT

01:38.018 --> 01:38.899
Yeah, you can give them a hand.

01:38.919 --> 01:40.581
They did a great job on that video.

01:46.047 --> 01:47.608
Okay, here's why I'm carrying this bag.

01:49.390 --> 01:50.491
We all carry baggage.

01:52.293 --> 01:52.694
All of us.

01:54.736 --> 01:56.838
It's not something that we naturally talk about.

01:56.878 --> 02:04.146
It's not something that we like to open up about a lot, but we do.

02:05.538 --> 02:17.556
The truth is, rather than talking about it, what we try to do is we try to create the image, the perception around us, that makes it look like we don't carry baggage.

02:19.319 --> 02:27.231
You know, those other broken people, home and poor them, but not us, all the while, and it's easy for other people to see generally.

02:28.813 --> 02:32.038
We're carrying baggage.

02:33.540 --> 02:34.802
And I have to tell you,

02:36.706 --> 02:40.011
I see myself a little bit too much in the mirror of that video.

02:40.031 --> 02:50.186
I told our video team and I appreciate their creativity in helping us tell the truth and show God's love and create the narrative.

02:50.246 --> 02:55.795
But I really didn't like that video because it was a little too real.

02:57.277 --> 02:59.120
I said, can't you be more abstract?

02:59.200 --> 03:01.643
So none of us have to deal with our own reality, right?

03:01.723 --> 03:06.130
I see myself all the way through that video.

03:07.106 --> 03:10.550
Me, me, me, me.

03:10.951 --> 03:12.312
Could you see yourself at all?

03:13.274 --> 03:16.217
If you couldn't, I'll give you a moment you can leave.

03:19.181 --> 03:20.543
You people scare us to death.

03:20.583 --> 03:21.143
That's the truth.

03:21.203 --> 03:23.166
I mean, if you can't see yourself in that.

03:23.847 --> 03:36.242
What's so sad about the reality of the baggage that we carry is that Jesus came to set us free from that very baggage.

03:37.762 --> 03:46.070
How he inspired Paul to say in Galatians 5, it is for freedom that Christ has set us free.

03:47.231 --> 03:56.701
So stand firm in that freedom and don't let yourselves be burdened again by a yoke of slavery.

03:58.423 --> 04:00.004
He came to set us free.

04:00.044 --> 04:05.810
And what's sad is that very often, and remember I've already included myself,

04:05.890 --> 04:16.446
Very often, we're sitting here singing songs of worship to Jesus who set us free all the while holding on to our baggage.

04:18.449 --> 04:30.007
Listening to His truth, which is meant to help us to experience the freedom He came to give us, but all the while clutching our baggage everywhere we go.

04:31.349 --> 04:34.354
And you need to know that sadly, sadly,

04:34.978 --> 04:38.923
It describes the majority of us, almost always.

04:39.864 --> 05:01.970
And so this series, aptly called baggage, is through prayer and design and study to try and help support each and every one of us find in our lives his truth, apply it to our reality and the baggage we carry and perhaps

05:02.786 --> 05:12.075
make the choice to experience Jesus' gift of freedom because it's for freedom Jesus has come to set us free.

05:13.257 --> 05:15.359
Now the truth is there are a lot of reasons for baggage.

05:15.739 --> 05:19.183
You know, the baggage I carry looks different than the baggage you carry.

05:19.443 --> 05:20.063
You can see it.

05:20.103 --> 05:21.845
I mean, all the suitcases are different.

05:21.885 --> 05:30.514
Some of you have those cute little pink things on the handle so you can identify them and some of you, I mean, we all have different baggage.

05:31.714 --> 05:35.979
There are some umbrella issues that all of us can experience.

05:37.240 --> 05:38.682
Yeah, that's me, that's me.

05:39.002 --> 05:47.271
And I wanted to kick this series off, which is going to last the month of May, by dealing with one of those umbrella baggages that we carry.

05:47.931 --> 05:48.812
It's a big one.

05:49.293 --> 05:55.520
All of us have experienced it in different ways, and it's just one word, hurt, hurts.

05:56.841 --> 06:01.426
Every single one of us has experienced the pain

06:01.602 --> 06:06.769
the agony, the disappoint, the despondency of hurts.

06:07.510 --> 06:12.416
In fact, many of us are held hostage to our hurts.

06:13.438 --> 06:15.641
It's for freedom, Christ has set us free.

06:16.241 --> 06:19.406
Don't be burdened again with the yoke of slavery.

06:19.666 --> 06:20.407
And yet, guess what?

06:20.747 --> 06:21.829
We're carrying our baggage.

06:23.691 --> 06:25.714
And much of it comes from hurts.

06:26.402 --> 06:32.675
So what I thought I'd do is just start with some realities that will help each of us kind of identify you.

06:33.256 --> 06:34.118
I have it too.

06:34.539 --> 06:38.187
And then we can process through what we can do about it, how we can lay it down.

06:38.908 --> 06:45.362
The first reality, and you need to know it, bad news, is that life comes with hurts included.

06:46.722 --> 06:53.053
I know when you go to the store, almost always the toy says, batteries not included, right?

06:53.474 --> 06:58.362
And I wish I could tell you, oh, some of us have been given life where hurts aren't included.

06:58.503 --> 06:59.104
It's not true.

06:59.484 --> 07:00.126
Now it is true.

07:00.566 --> 07:03.251
Some people's hurts are far more obvious than others.

07:04.153 --> 07:08.520
Some are seemingly way more devastating than others.

07:08.781 --> 07:11.826
Let's be honest about that, but just know.

07:12.098 --> 07:15.281
All of us experience hurts, the pain of hurts.

07:15.702 --> 07:21.849
None of us can understand the hurts of others from the outside looking in, but life comes with hurts included.

07:21.869 --> 07:23.771
I love how the Bible's honest about this.

07:23.811 --> 07:33.962
Psalm chapter nine, D verse 10, the length of our days, let's say at 70 years or 80, if we have the strength to live that long, yet here's the reality that defines them all.

07:34.402 --> 07:38.987
Their span is but trouble and sorrow, for they quickly pass and we fly away.

07:40.289 --> 07:41.490
We all experience

07:41.826 --> 07:42.167
hurts.

07:42.728 --> 07:43.950
They come included in life.

07:44.251 --> 07:53.108
Hurts can be physical, hurts can be emotional, hurts can be spiritual, hurts can be relational, but hurts are real.

07:53.909 --> 07:55.933
And they're part of the baggage that we carry in life.

07:57.496 --> 08:02.245
The truth is that hurts can be caused by ourselves.

08:04.069 --> 08:04.850
If I'm honest,

08:04.930 --> 08:07.775
Most of my deepest wounds weren't caused by others.

08:07.876 --> 08:11.543
Most of my deepest wounds were caused by myself, the choices I made.

08:11.923 --> 08:12.745
Can you relate to that?

08:12.985 --> 08:19.137
I like to blame others, but it's often myself.

08:19.157 --> 08:25.329
But hurts can be delivered through others where no fault of our own.

08:25.950 --> 08:28.114
People betray us, break promises.

08:30.690 --> 08:33.735
But the reality is it's not even always ourselves or others.

08:33.955 --> 08:43.870
Do you know, sometimes hurts are just part of the unpredictable and uncontrollable parts of life, changing circumstances.

08:43.910 --> 08:56.850
There's a bumper sticker and I'd love to use it in this case, but I'm in church and I'm a pastor and some of you are guests and others of you wouldn't come again if I

08:57.474 --> 09:15.206
shared the bumper sticker, so I'm not gonna share the bumper sticker, but I am going to share the bumper sticker with a different word and let you think of the real bumper sticker so that you can carry just a little bit more baggage out of Northridge after you leave, okay?

09:15.847 --> 09:17.911
And here's the bumper sticker.

09:19.173 --> 09:19.835
My version of it.

09:20.636 --> 09:21.778
Stuff happens.

09:25.378 --> 09:27.721
Sometimes it's not my fault, another person's fault.

09:28.342 --> 09:30.224
Circumstances have converged on me.

09:30.665 --> 09:32.628
Stuff happens and it hurts.

09:33.128 --> 09:35.311
Hurts are included in life.

09:35.852 --> 09:42.781
And another reality, our best attempts to free ourselves from hurt because no one likes to sit in hurts.

09:44.523 --> 09:45.224
It's not what we do.

09:45.244 --> 09:52.754
Our best attempts to free ourselves from hurts leave us in greater bondage to them.

09:53.698 --> 09:56.342
So the very thing that Jesus says, I've come to set you free.

09:56.682 --> 10:06.877
I don't want you to be burdened again with yoga bondage, but the way we go about trying to deliver ourselves from hurts puts us in greater bondage to them.

10:08.219 --> 10:12.846
And I tell you, I don't purposely try to expand the hurt in my life.

10:13.507 --> 10:18.354
That's not my deal, but yet I do it by

10:19.394 --> 10:27.163
Choosing to try and get past my hurts in the wrong ways, feeling like it's the right way, and it just devastates me even more.

10:27.424 --> 10:30.848
Bible talks a lot about this idea, one place, Proverbs 14, 12.

10:31.288 --> 10:34.072
There is a way that appears to be right, and this is where I am.

10:34.412 --> 10:35.934
Man, this is how I can get out of this hurt.

10:35.954 --> 10:37.616
This is how I can free myself from the pain.

10:37.656 --> 10:42.121
This is what I'll do to get past it, but in the end, it leads to death.

10:42.942 --> 10:44.604
Same thing happens to you.

10:44.744 --> 10:46.226
It's just the way life is.

10:47.394 --> 10:55.406
By nature, we tend to deal with life's hurts in a way that brings about the exact opposite result to what we're seeking in our lives.

10:55.786 --> 11:01.314
Our natural attempt is to minimize our hurts, but it almost always maximizes them.

11:01.615 --> 11:04.419
And the neat thing about the Bible is that it's a real book.

11:04.459 --> 11:07.183
It's not one of these things that plays make-believe about humanity.

11:07.483 --> 11:08.264
It tells the truth.

11:08.645 --> 11:11.809
And God's given us a beautiful picture of this in many lives.

11:11.849 --> 11:14.994
But what I want to share with you is the example of David.

11:15.746 --> 11:17.449
Now David's often known as a hero.

11:17.729 --> 11:20.874
He's the one that stood against Goliath and took him down by faith.

11:20.914 --> 11:23.678
You know, King David, awesome guy, man after God's own heart.

11:23.698 --> 11:31.329
But the reality is David was a human being, flawed like me, flawed like you, and man did he have a lot of baggage.

11:33.112 --> 11:39.762
And he went about trying to deliver himself in the wrong way, and it even made it worse.

11:40.802 --> 11:43.365
Now with David, he brought some of the hurts on himself.

11:43.725 --> 11:48.069
Some of the hurts were delivered by others, and some were just the convergence of stuff happening.

11:48.390 --> 11:57.319
But more often than not, like us, it was how he tried to deal with his hurts that ultimately destroyed him.

11:57.339 --> 11:59.301
And I think we can learn from that, and I know I can.

12:00.061 --> 12:01.903
So let me just share some angles.

12:02.664 --> 12:08.690
One thing David did to try and deliver himself from hearts, and it made it worse, is he attempted to deny

12:09.378 --> 12:10.419
literally deny us hurts.

12:10.439 --> 12:15.004
And this is where we both start with denial.

12:15.605 --> 12:16.967
And you know the stupid joke, right?

12:17.027 --> 12:20.431
Something that an old guy should say, and I'm not talking about a river in Egypt.

12:20.451 --> 12:22.333
You know, I mean, it's like denial.

12:22.693 --> 12:25.016
It's a really popular thing.

12:25.797 --> 12:26.558
And that's where we start.

12:26.918 --> 12:29.020
If I can just deny it, I'll do it.

12:29.321 --> 12:30.522
Deny, deny, deny.

12:30.542 --> 12:32.825
And that's what David did, Psalm 32, three.

12:33.405 --> 12:37.490
When I kept silent, when I denied it, oh, it just,

12:37.570 --> 12:39.933
enlarged in my life and started destroying me.

12:39.993 --> 12:43.537
My bones wasted away through my groaning all day long.

12:44.037 --> 12:45.379
It only makes it worse.

12:47.241 --> 12:48.082
Have you ever denied?

12:48.102 --> 12:49.704
I have.

12:53.107 --> 13:02.578
He also, trying to deliver himself, made things worse by fantasizing about running away from his hurts.

13:03.234 --> 13:08.181
You know, dreaming of ways to escape them and run beyond them.

13:08.321 --> 13:12.306
And creative people definitely do this.

13:12.386 --> 13:12.967
He was one.

13:13.007 --> 13:17.033
Look at Psalm 55, my heart is an anguish within me.

13:17.393 --> 13:18.915
Man, I'm just in pain.

13:19.376 --> 13:20.878
And so he starts fantasizing.

13:20.898 --> 13:22.540
Oh, that I had the wings of a dove.

13:22.600 --> 13:24.303
I would fly away and be at rest.

13:24.343 --> 13:27.327
I would flee far away and stay in the desert.

13:28.588 --> 13:29.970
And you might go, get it.

13:30.851 --> 13:32.754
Listen, I do this all the time.

13:33.026 --> 13:38.515
I dream of all the ways that I can get past this stuff without really dealing it.

13:39.236 --> 13:39.877
That's where he was.

13:40.558 --> 13:41.700
And it just makes it worse.

13:42.661 --> 13:43.643
I would bet money you do it.

13:45.766 --> 13:47.469
Not that I really bet money.

13:48.791 --> 13:50.774
Trying to avoid emails this week.

13:53.117 --> 13:55.722
As you think, I just have a little baggage.

13:57.384 --> 13:58.225
Trying to deal with it.

13:58.286 --> 13:58.546
All right.

13:58.987 --> 14:01.170
As you think about your life,

14:01.442 --> 14:15.223
Let me ask you, is it possible that some or a lot of your activity in life is simply an attempt to escape or run away from life's hurts?

14:18.648 --> 14:25.519
If so, you need to realize that none of us are fast enough to stay in front of the hurts.

14:25.639 --> 14:26.680
We can't do it.

14:27.782 --> 14:30.386
And ultimately, we only hurt ourselves

14:30.466 --> 14:32.470
even more by running.

14:32.711 --> 14:48.946
And I'm talking about what are some ways we try and do it through work, through this relationship to the next relationship to the next relationship, through some of the addictive aspects of life that we have through spirituality.

14:49.858 --> 14:52.501
and religion, trying to just run away.

14:52.901 --> 14:54.803
But you know, the more we run, the worse it gets.

14:54.863 --> 14:59.067
It's kind of like quicksand when you attempt to run away, you just sink deeper and deeper and deeper.

14:59.328 --> 15:01.990
And that's exactly what happens with us.

15:03.932 --> 15:08.637
Another thing David did wrong that I can relate with sadly is that he sought to hide his hurts.

15:08.937 --> 15:14.443
When he could no longer deny them, you know, couldn't fantasize about ways to get away from them.

15:15.324 --> 15:17.426
He sought to hide his hurts.

15:17.666 --> 15:25.978
You know, I already said this, we create a perception, an image around us, that makes it look like we're not carrying baggage at all.

15:27.340 --> 15:44.126
Look at David, did it Psalm 39 starting verse two, but when I was silent and still, not even saying anything good, my anguish increased in me, my heart grew hot within me, and as I meditated, the fire burned, and I finally spoke with my tongue.

15:44.747 --> 15:47.090
The thing is, he was trying to hide it,

15:48.226 --> 15:49.968
pretend that it wasn't real, not me.

15:50.008 --> 15:51.670
No, I'm fine and all that stuff.

15:51.690 --> 15:54.053
He didn't want anyone to know that he was hurting.

15:55.395 --> 16:00.321
And even though he was in the valley, he wanted people to think he was on the mountaintop.

16:00.381 --> 16:06.348
And though this is a very strange way to approach pain, it's a very natural one.

16:06.769 --> 16:07.450
We all do it.

16:08.591 --> 16:13.537
It's about image over reality.

16:14.979 --> 16:15.960
And here's the idea.

16:15.980 --> 16:17.682
It's that if people

16:18.210 --> 16:23.496
think well of us, then hey, we'll feel better about ourselves.

16:25.078 --> 16:33.168
If you look at me with these eyes of respect, maybe I'll feel more respect for myself.

16:33.568 --> 16:35.511
So we create these images.

16:35.971 --> 16:39.255
Unfortunately, this doesn't work, and yet we've all been there.

16:39.836 --> 16:40.457
We've all tried.

16:41.478 --> 16:48.146
So could I ask, could it be this weekend that you have everyone around you convinced

16:48.962 --> 16:52.186
that you're on the mountaintop.

16:52.206 --> 16:54.729
But in reality, you're in a very deep dark valley.

16:54.989 --> 16:55.450
Could it be?

16:55.510 --> 17:04.861
Isn't it amazing how many seemingly perfect marriages break up?

17:06.824 --> 17:07.725
They were never perfect.

17:08.886 --> 17:11.169
These people were creating the perception.

17:13.191 --> 17:18.578
Isn't it amazing how many people who seem to be so much better than the rest of us fall apart?

17:18.818 --> 17:21.481
and break down, they're not better than us.

17:23.222 --> 17:25.064
They've just been hiding more.

17:25.825 --> 17:26.506
It never works.

17:27.567 --> 17:38.078
Can I tell you, and I hope you'll process this, the greatest bondage in the world is found in having to live up to something you're not.

17:40.640 --> 17:41.281
It's destructive.

17:41.581 --> 17:46.386
You wonder why so many pastors surprisingly fall

17:48.546 --> 17:57.882
Because they pretended they were something they weren't, and the gravity of it finally became too much.

17:59.344 --> 18:03.712
Which is why I just get up and cuss in front of you, tell the truth, if I'm a mess.

18:03.732 --> 18:06.196
It's like, no pretending here.

18:07.959 --> 18:10.684
A little bit of hyperbole there, but it's true.

18:11.365 --> 18:11.986
Doesn't work.

18:12.866 --> 18:16.572
The greatest freedom in the world is not found in hiding.

18:16.612 --> 18:25.387
The greatest freedom in the world is found in being honest because it's for freedom that Jesus came.

18:27.630 --> 18:28.652
We have to be honest.

18:28.752 --> 18:30.495
We have to make the right choices.

18:30.555 --> 18:32.338
You know another thing David did wrong, I do.

18:32.699 --> 18:37.266
He worried about his hurts.

18:37.666 --> 18:43.354
Look at how he says Psalm 52 5, 2, my thoughts trouble me and I am distraught.

18:43.374 --> 18:46.759
I mean, it was an agony and silence all the way inside man.

18:47.540 --> 18:49.122
It just never gets you anywhere.

18:49.182 --> 18:53.428
What does worrying about your hurts do to relieve you of your hurts?

18:53.448 --> 18:54.029
Nothing.

18:54.669 --> 19:01.038
In fact, the result is your hurts become larger because the more you focus on them, the bigger they get.

19:01.058 --> 19:03.762
It's like you've got a zoom lens on your hurts, you know?

19:07.426 --> 19:11.331
Another thing he did that I can relate to, is he allowed his hurts to ultimately define him.

19:11.351 --> 19:13.113
I need to tell you something.

19:13.974 --> 19:15.315
Your hurts are not you.

19:17.758 --> 19:27.750
But too often, by hiding, by denying, by running, all this stuff that we do, we start seeing ourselves as our hurts.

19:29.032 --> 19:30.213
It defines who we are.

19:31.515 --> 19:32.076
And it's wrong.

19:32.116 --> 19:33.838
Look at how David said it in Psalm 38.

19:33.918 --> 19:37.362
I am feeble and utterly crushed.

19:37.858 --> 19:39.541
God says he's a man after his own heart.

19:40.502 --> 19:42.225
I am feeble and utterly crushed.

19:42.305 --> 19:43.987
I groan in anguish of heart.

19:44.067 --> 19:45.089
My heart pounds.

19:45.169 --> 19:46.271
My strength fails me.

19:46.411 --> 19:48.474
Even the light has gone from my eyes.

19:48.935 --> 19:50.858
My friends and companions avoid me.

19:50.898 --> 19:56.947
Of course they do because this is who I am because my wounds, my neighbors stay far away.

19:56.967 --> 20:00.632
He allowed his hurts to define him.

20:01.153 --> 20:01.854
And so do we.

20:03.256 --> 20:06.962
And so that's why I thought that video was so strong.

20:07.650 --> 20:09.572
I mean, the guy didn't know how to live without his hurts.

20:11.734 --> 20:12.175
Nor do we.

20:13.276 --> 20:14.157
It's just so natural.

20:15.358 --> 20:19.563
I want you to realize, none of his choices changed the past hurts in his life.

20:20.924 --> 20:22.206
But you know what his choices did?

20:23.247 --> 20:25.710
They ruined the present day of his life.

20:27.111 --> 20:28.352
And that's what happens to us.

20:30.455 --> 20:33.458
But we can make a different choice.

20:35.042 --> 20:42.933
And so there's no way to give good news until we know what the bad news is, and so we know what the bad news is about baggage and hurts, but now we need the good news.

20:43.313 --> 20:45.276
And it comes right from the same guy, from David.

20:45.596 --> 20:51.484
David ultimately chose to let God set him free from his hurts.

20:52.806 --> 21:00.396
This one who hid and denied and ran and all this other stuff, he ultimately chose to let God free him from his hurts.

21:00.717 --> 21:04.562
What he did was he made the different choice.

21:05.634 --> 21:12.342
And the problem is, too many of us are so holding on to our baggage, we won't let it go.

21:12.362 --> 21:17.328
But we can, we need to, and David did.

21:17.669 --> 21:18.670
And he shows us how.

21:18.710 --> 21:25.939
Here's how he got from where we are naturally to where he experienced life without his baggage.

21:26.219 --> 21:29.964
He got there first by never giving up on God.

21:30.244 --> 21:33.829
He never gave up on God.

21:33.849 --> 21:34.930
As human beings,

21:35.170 --> 21:36.955
It's almost the starting place for us.

21:37.376 --> 21:45.537
You know people in your life, in all different walks of life, from all different backgrounds and experiences who've given up on God.

21:46.238 --> 21:49.266
We're living in a world where data can show us

21:49.570 --> 21:52.593
Tons of people are walking away from the God thing.

21:52.613 --> 21:53.975
I'm not talking about church, Jess.

21:54.075 --> 21:55.216
I'm talking about God.

21:55.577 --> 21:56.618
They're giving up on Him.

21:56.858 --> 21:58.620
It's a failed experience in their mind.

21:58.660 --> 22:01.383
They're not going to pursue that anymore because they hurt.

22:01.423 --> 22:03.586
The problem, though, isn't God.

22:03.606 --> 22:11.534
The problem is they keep trying to deal with their hurts their own way and claim God's promises of freedom and they don't experience it.

22:12.876 --> 22:14.898
David, who's just like us,

22:15.362 --> 22:18.850
The one thing he did right was he never gave up on God.

22:19.051 --> 22:26.909
Look at how he said it in Psalm 130 verse one, out of the depths of my pain, I cry to you, O Lord.

22:27.751 --> 22:29.194
It's one of the things I love about the Psalms.

22:30.818 --> 22:32.562
Guys like David, they'd write,

22:32.642 --> 22:33.783
The world's horrible.

22:33.843 --> 22:35.245
You don't answer my prayers.

22:35.305 --> 22:36.586
Where are your promises?

22:36.647 --> 22:38.549
The sun's not coming out tomorrow.

22:38.589 --> 22:42.693
I'm like the character in childhood brown with the cloud over their head following them around.

22:43.094 --> 22:44.455
Life's nothing like what you said.

22:44.496 --> 22:47.339
And then at the very end, they go, but I'll always praise you.

22:47.359 --> 22:47.919
You're awesome.

22:47.939 --> 22:50.843
It's like, what's going on?

22:51.363 --> 22:55.048
I almost said a word that would have proved that I'm normal.

22:55.348 --> 22:56.629
It's like, what's going on?

22:59.553 --> 23:00.754
He never gave up on God.

23:02.018 --> 23:03.220
No matter how bad it got.

23:05.524 --> 23:10.132
And because of that, David ultimately realized that God was bigger than his trouble, bigger than his hurts.

23:10.693 --> 23:12.155
And I want to encourage you this weekend.

23:13.437 --> 23:14.740
God's bigger than your pain.

23:16.983 --> 23:17.304
He is.

23:17.564 --> 23:18.546
Don't give up on him.

23:20.450 --> 23:24.014
How did David get there to where he made the different choice and laid it down?

23:24.515 --> 23:26.457
He acknowledged his hurts to God.

23:26.858 --> 23:27.739
What do we naturally do?

23:27.979 --> 23:31.904
Hide them, deny them, create the perceptions, not run from them.

23:31.924 --> 23:37.131
But he ultimately did the opposite, made the choice to acknowledge his hurts to God.

23:37.752 --> 23:44.360
Here's how he says it, Psalm 32, when I kept silent, my bones wasted away, we've already seen that, but then what did he do?

23:44.860 --> 23:49.426
Then I acknowledged my sin, sin.

23:49.730 --> 23:57.357
Self-motivated, his self-delivered hurt where he walked away from God.

23:57.717 --> 24:02.122
I acknowledged my sin to you and did not cover up my iniquity.

24:02.522 --> 24:08.087
And you forgave the guilt of my horrible choices, my sin.

24:09.408 --> 24:10.129
He acknowledged it.

24:10.970 --> 24:11.771
It's not natural.

24:11.791 --> 24:12.892
It's not what we want to do.

24:13.893 --> 24:18.016
But the only way we can lay our baggage down is by acknowledging our hurts to God.

24:18.357 --> 24:19.698
And the last thing he did

24:20.610 --> 24:30.182
To make the choice, he turned to and trusted God with his hurts instead of turning to and trusting his own devices.

24:32.084 --> 24:39.534
The whole reason I started this conversation out by saying, here's the way we normally handle it is because that's the way we really normally handle it.

24:41.316 --> 24:49.266
But Jesus has made it possible for us to be set free, but in order to be there, we have to make the different choice.

24:49.794 --> 24:54.720
Stop trusting ourselves and start trusting Him with our pain.

24:55.041 --> 24:59.386
Look at what He said in Psalm 142, I pour out my complaint before Him.

24:59.446 --> 25:01.449
Before Him, I tell all my trouble.

25:02.150 --> 25:07.837
When my spirit grows faint within me, it is you, God, who know the way I should go.

25:09.139 --> 25:12.263
Listen to my cry, for I'm in desperate need.

25:13.024 --> 25:17.810
Rescue me from those who pursue me, for they are too strong for me.

25:19.362 --> 25:25.650
In the early days of his life, he couldn't say, they're too strong for me.

25:26.591 --> 25:27.152
I'll do this.

25:27.212 --> 25:27.712
I'll do this.

25:27.753 --> 25:28.213
I'll do this.

25:28.273 --> 25:29.054
It messed up everything.

25:29.134 --> 25:32.719
And then he got to the place where he said, they're too strong for me.

25:33.860 --> 25:34.661
I need to trust you.

25:36.143 --> 25:44.754
What we're doing here this weekend is we're asking you to identify the reality that, like with all of us, you carry baggage.

25:47.597 --> 25:48.018
And it's

25:48.130 --> 25:48.891
ruining your life.

25:48.951 --> 25:49.852
It's hurting your life.

25:49.932 --> 25:51.054
It's destroying your life.

25:51.535 --> 25:52.816
It is not the right way to go.

25:53.257 --> 25:58.264
And you, by nature, like all of us, have been trying to deal with it in the wrong way.

25:59.606 --> 26:06.435
But we want you to finally do what David did, make a different choice, and lay him down.

26:06.475 --> 26:11.943
So he laid down his baggage.

26:16.109 --> 26:17.010
But it wasn't easy.

26:18.754 --> 26:22.019
And if we're gonna lay down our baggage, we have to know it's not easy.

26:22.079 --> 26:27.428
And so we thought, okay, now that we know that it's possible, what's it look like?

26:27.688 --> 26:28.810
What's it feel like?

26:31.174 --> 26:41.290
So we decided we'd paint a picture for you of what it might be like for you if you were to consider laying down your baggage.

26:42.412 --> 26:46.258
What might happen to you, can you really do it?

26:47.202 --> 26:53.183
And so we want you to contemplate, we want you to watch, we want to identify yourself as we paint this picture.

26:53.243 --> 26:59.666
But the goal is to get you, like David, to finally lay it down.

32:19.650 --> 32:25.038
I don't know about for you, but for me, that picture is so emotional.

32:28.202 --> 32:29.544
Because it's so real.

32:29.564 --> 32:40.520
I mean, yeah, there are some people who come and just lay their burdens down and walk away and they never see themselves through those burdens again.

32:42.043 --> 32:44.386
But that's not everybody.

32:44.406 --> 32:47.090
I don't know if you noticed, there were some people who came

32:48.418 --> 32:53.143
laid their burdens down and then came back and picked them back up.

32:55.245 --> 32:56.026
And I know that one.

32:59.329 --> 33:01.471
That's why Jesus says it's for freedom, I've set you free.

33:02.792 --> 33:05.575
Don't be burdened again with your yoke of bondage.

33:05.595 --> 33:09.219
I've delivered you from it, but we can still see ourselves through it.

33:10.700 --> 33:16.626
And then, the last one with that couple, where the husband put his

33:16.930 --> 33:22.958
and she just wouldn't let go of it, which is where most people are.

33:22.978 --> 33:32.011
What you need to know is holding on to your hurts solves nothing, which is why Jesus came.

33:33.713 --> 33:35.415
Might be one of my favorite crosses ever.

33:35.455 --> 33:37.278
We've made a cross out of baggage.

33:37.338 --> 33:37.598
Why?

33:38.259 --> 33:40.342
Because that's what the cross was for.

33:40.763 --> 33:46.130
For Jesus to take all of our baggage on himself and deliver us from it.

33:47.298 --> 34:07.966
But the only way we get delivered is by never giving up on God, acknowledging our hurt, our sin, our guilt to Him, and then turning to Him and trusting Him by laying our baggage down at the foot of the cross.

34:10.009 --> 34:10.530
Have you done it?

34:11.852 --> 34:13.434
Here's the truth you need to know.

34:13.835 --> 34:16.338
Jesus can set us free.

34:16.578 --> 34:17.520
from our hurts.

34:19.405 --> 34:24.157
John 836 says, so if the sun sets you free, you are free indeed.

34:24.718 --> 34:25.360
You're free.

34:25.941 --> 34:34.322
Nothing can make those define you anymore, but you can still define yourself through them, which is where so many of us are.

34:35.330 --> 34:37.733
So the application, we learned it from David.

34:37.753 --> 34:38.995
We need to do it ourselves.

34:39.476 --> 34:49.549
We need to, if we're going to lay it down at the foot of the cross, we need to focus on Jesus rather than focusing on our hurts.

34:52.233 --> 34:56.839
But rather, we sit at the diner and eat looking at our hurts and focused on them.

34:56.919 --> 34:58.742
We sleep focusing on our hurts.

34:58.802 --> 35:00.464
We wake up focusing on our hurts.

35:00.484 --> 35:02.206
We drive focusing on our hurts.

35:02.527 --> 35:05.010
We walk our dog focusing on our hurts.

35:05.122 --> 35:08.747
All of life, which is why all we do is hurt.

35:09.368 --> 35:17.699
But when we make the choice to lay it down for the cross and focus on Jesus, he sets us free.

35:18.740 --> 35:25.009
John 1633, these things I've said unto you, Jesus said, that in me, you can have peace.

35:26.491 --> 35:27.933
In the world, you're gonna have trouble.

35:27.973 --> 35:32.679
Life comes with hurts included, but be of good cheer.

35:33.740 --> 35:34.962
I've overcome the world.

35:36.546 --> 35:38.269
You know who the people with cheer are?

35:38.729 --> 35:46.641
The people focusing on Jesus, which explains most of our problems.

35:47.182 --> 35:47.622
We're not.

35:48.784 --> 35:55.474
And so before we celebrate communion, I just want to give you a moment to reflect, to focus on Him.

35:56.162 --> 35:58.906
to be honest with yourself about your baggage.

35:58.966 --> 36:02.011
So would you bow with me in a word of prayer wherever you are?

36:02.432 --> 36:07.820
Those that brighten, those here implement, those of you online, would you just kind of bow on a word of prayer?

36:09.623 --> 36:16.894
And for those of you who are followers of Jesus, yes, if you've taken your baggage and laid it down at the cross, you've given him your sin.

36:17.355 --> 36:22.543
It's forgiven and you've been set free, but it doesn't mean you're not still carrying the baggage.

36:23.885 --> 36:24.626
You need to.

36:25.346 --> 36:26.607
focus on Jesus again.

36:28.749 --> 36:40.261
And there are some of you while others are praying already that you've never, ever taken your hurts, your pain, your sin, and laid it down at the foot of the cross.

36:42.463 --> 36:43.243
Why not do it now?

36:45.986 --> 36:49.329
In fact, just pray with me, with these words, make them your own.

36:49.410 --> 36:54.034
Just say, Jesus, I've been carrying the weight of my

36:54.146 --> 36:57.091
Sin, my guilt, my pain.

36:59.335 --> 37:08.550
But I believe that you came to take it from me, to forgive me, to bear my burdens for me.

37:10.253 --> 37:14.580
And so I'm acknowledging my guilt, my hurt, my pain, my sin.

37:14.620 --> 37:20.690
And I'm laying it down at your cross, trusting you.

37:22.178 --> 37:25.782
and asking you to forgive me and save me and make me free.

37:27.384 --> 37:28.285
In Jesus' name.

37:29.747 --> 37:30.067
Amen.

37:31.028 --> 37:36.294
Now, if you prayed with me, we'd love to give you some ideas and support and moving forward.

37:36.334 --> 37:38.617
We're not gonna obnoxiously come into your life.

37:38.657 --> 37:44.924
We'd love to give you a book of the Bible and journal form, ideas for how you can build your relationship with God and how we might support that.

37:45.265 --> 37:46.606
We just need to know you prayed with me.

37:47.067 --> 37:48.028
All you have to do is text us.

37:48.609 --> 37:49.810
One word, Northridge,

37:50.306 --> 37:51.447
That's the message to 31616.

37:53.129 --> 37:57.134
We'll send you a link, you fill that out, get it back to us, and we'll send you that information.

37:57.214 --> 38:03.281
But for all of us now, what we want to do is we want to focus on Jesus instead of our hurts.

38:03.301 --> 38:04.202
We want to lay it down.

38:04.763 --> 38:06.905
And you know what the perfect way to do that is?

38:08.147 --> 38:08.647
Communion.

38:09.728 --> 38:13.413
Jesus gave us one word as the purpose for communion.

38:14.033 --> 38:14.674
Remember.

38:15.938 --> 38:19.522
My problem isn't that Jesus hasn't set me free.

38:20.022 --> 38:22.665
My problem is that I forget.

38:22.705 --> 38:36.060
And so I live my life through my weakness, and through my failures, and through my bad choices, and I define myself like that, and I live to deny it, and hide it, and so do you, carrying my burden.

38:36.080 --> 38:39.063
But all the while, if I focus on Jesus, what happens?

38:40.085 --> 38:42.407
Oh, I remember I'm free.

38:42.427 --> 38:45.010
So communion is.

38:45.890 --> 38:49.317
He gave us the bread to remind us of his body.

38:49.377 --> 38:54.748
He gave us the juice to remind us of his blood that was shed to forgive us of our sins.

38:54.829 --> 38:58.116
And so, by eating and drinking, we remember.

38:58.536 --> 38:59.859
But here's what I want to say.

38:59.919 --> 39:06.994
If you've never put your faith in Jesus, then you have nothing to remember, but your hurts.

39:08.226 --> 39:18.745
And at any moment, you can put your faith in Jesus, but if you haven't, then communion's not for you because this is for people who can remember when, by faith, they receive Jesus.

39:21.189 --> 39:26.338
There's no judgment at Northridge, so if you don't know Him or you're not walking with Him, it's okay not to take.

39:28.402 --> 39:33.170
But if you are walking with Him and if you do know Him, we want you to remember.

39:34.434 --> 39:37.798
And so you'll take the bread and the juice will do it together.

39:38.019 --> 39:39.420
But first, let's pray.

39:40.281 --> 39:46.670
Father in heaven, I thank you for this moment when we can remember that it's for freedom you've set us free.

39:48.011 --> 39:49.794
And we can turn our focus back to you.

39:49.854 --> 39:56.743
And so through communion, we now remember in Jesus' name, amen.

39:56.783 --> 40:02.610
And so we take the bread and eat it in remembrance of Him.

40:09.922 --> 40:12.426
and we drink the juice in remembrance of Him.

40:16.773 --> 40:24.605
And in remembering, we lay the baggage down and we walk in freedom.

40:25.547 --> 40:27.289
And you know what the great response is to that?

40:27.810 --> 40:30.134
Worship, celebration.

40:30.715 --> 40:35.683
And so that's what we're gonna do, but we're going to add a component this weekend as we worship.

40:36.083 --> 40:37.746
We're also going to be baptizing.

40:38.466 --> 40:42.893
This weekend alone, over a hundred people are being baptized at Northridge Church.

40:42.953 --> 40:49.084
It's an awesome thing.

40:49.104 --> 40:52.149
And if you're a guest at Northridge, we do it in a unique way.

40:52.229 --> 40:57.778
We worship God because He's the only one that can make life change possible.

40:58.434 --> 41:03.259
But we also celebrate the people who are laying it down and following Him in baptism.

41:03.339 --> 41:10.627
And so you're going to, it's weird, we'll be singing worship songs and then all of a sudden people will start whistling and cheering and clapping as people are being baptized.

41:10.647 --> 41:13.089
Some people will do backflips off the seats of their chairs.

41:13.169 --> 41:13.710
No, they won't.

41:14.250 --> 41:14.691
No, they won't.

41:15.312 --> 41:16.873
But it's a celebration.

41:17.133 --> 41:21.918
But it's a celebration of what God has done and steps they've taken.

41:22.019 --> 41:25.362
So together, let's celebrate these being baptized.

